aws-transcripts.transcript: I was around 10 when one day I discovered a box of my father's old things. In it, under a bunch of his college textbooks was a pair of black corduroy bell bottom bands. These plans were awful musty and Martha Eaton and of course, I fell in love with them. I've never seen anything like them until that day. All that ever known and born was my school uniform, which in fact, I was pretty grateful for because from quite a young age, I'd realized I was somewhat different. I've never been one of the boys my age, terrible at sports, possibly the unmanned, liest little boy ever. I was believed quite a bit, And so I figured that to survive, I would be invisible, and the uniform helped me to seem no different from any other child. Well, almost this became my daily prayer. God, please make me just like everybody else. I think this went straight to God's voice mail, though, and eventually it became pretty clear that it was not growing up to be the son that my father always wanted. Sorry, Dad. No, I was not going to magically change an overtime. I grew less and less sure that I actually wanted to. Therefore, the day those black corduroy bell bottom pants came into my life, something happened. I didn't see bands. I saw opportunity. The very next day I had to wear them to school. Come what may and once I pulled on those God awful parents and belted them tight. Almost instantly, I developed what can only be called a swagger all the way to school and then all the way back because of a sent home. At once, I transformed into a little brown rock star. I find it and care anymore that I could not conform that day. I was suddenly celebrating it. That day, Instead of being invisible, I chose to be looked at just by burying something different. That day I discovered the power off what we wear that day. I discovered the power of fashion, and I've been in love with it ever since. Fashion can communicate our differences to the world for us and with the simple act of truth. I realized that these differences they stopped being our shame that became our expressions. Expressions off are very unique identities, and we should express ourselves where what we want. What's the worst that could happen? The fashion police are going to get you for being so last season. Hey, yeah, well, unless the fashion police meant something entirely different. Nobel Prize laureate Malala survive Taliban extremists in October 2012 However, in October 2000 and 17 she faced a different enemy when online trolls viciously attacked the photograph that showed the 20 year old wearing jeans that day. The comments, the hatred she received ranged from how long before the scarf comes off. Do and I quote, That's the reason the bullet directly targeted her head a long time ago. Now, when most of us decide to wear a pair of jeans someplace like New York, London, Milan, Paris, we possibly don't stop to think that it's a privilege, something that somewhere else can have consequences. Something that can one day be taken away from us. My grandmother was a woman who took extraordinary pleasure and dressing up. Her fashion was colorful on the color she loved to wear. So much was possibly the only thing that was truly about her.
